## Demo Context

This demo evaluates **ClarityWise** on a blinded, single-image radiology reasoning task.

The input was one static CT angiogram figure from a case involving a 64-year-old woman. ClarityWise was instructed to analyze only the visible image and image labels, without using the caption, DOI, article title, known answer, or outside case context.

The goal was not to replace a radiologist or produce a clinical diagnosis from one image. The goal was to test whether the system could structure radiology reasoning safely by separating:

- visible evidence;
- diagnostic inference;
- uncertainty;
- needed confirmation.

---

## Blinded Image-First Result

ClarityWise identified the image as a **cardiac/coronary CT angiogram** based on the visible **RCA** and **LCX** labels.

It recognized a complex abnormal vascular-appearing cluster adjacent to the heart, marked by asterisks on the figure. It also identified apparent relationships between the abnormality and both the right coronary artery and left circumflex artery territories.

The system described the lesion as a probable complex vascular abnormality and favored a **coronary fistula / coronary-cameral vascular communication or vascular malformation** as the leading diagnostic category.

It did not state a definitive named diagnosis because the drainage site and full vascular pathway were not safely established from the single still image alone.

That restraint was appropriate under the prompt constraints.

---

## Why the Structure Was Useful

The output was useful because it did not merely generate a radiology-style paragraph. It organized the reasoning into an audit-ready structure:

| Layer | Function |
|---|---|
| Visible evidence | What can actually be seen on the image |
| Interpretation | What the visible evidence may mean |
| Certainty | Whether the conclusion is definite, probable, possible, or unresolved |
| Needed confirmation | What additional data would be required before finalizing |

This format is valuable because it makes the reasoning inspectable. A radiologist can quickly see what the system saw, what it inferred, what it refused to infer, and what would be needed to confirm or correct the interpretation.

